menstruation on hormonal birth control is actually withdrawal bleeding - bleeding that occurs from the withdrawal of hormones. -this was created to give your body a break from the consistent level of hormones, and to mimic a menstrual cycle to try to comfort people who might feel worried about birth control (ex. some women back in the 1950s, when hormonal birth control was first created and released, were skeptical about it because it would change their menstrual cycle). -it's very similar to menstruation, with very similar symptoms and side effects, as hormone levels go down and fluctuate during this time with both. these vary with every person - some people's menstruation is better, some worse, and some the same. more commonly better, as, for example, cramps can improve due to no lining. there can still be some sort of cramping from the withdrawal bleeding, though. -you can actually skip this period (ha pun), as there's no lining to be shed, it's just a reaction from the lack of hormones. though only up to 6, sometimes 3 months (depending on what type you take, how many hormones you're taking, your health history, your side effects, etc), as the hormones can build up too much, to where they can cause death. everything else in this seems correct! i suggest looking up "withdrawal bleeding birth control" and reading more on it, if you're interested! good on you for reading this and educating yourself on the female reproductive system!
